d verbal domains also reflect parallel semantic categorisation of entities and events. The main topics investigated in this book are word class flexibility between nouns and verbs, non-finiteness, noun class/gender (where morphological classes are analysed separately from agreement classes) and the semantic principles underlying the categorisation of entities and events. One of the central findings proposed in this book is that instances of NCP alternations on non-finite verbs reflect strategies of event delimitation. This book will be of interest to scholars investigation parts-of-speech systems, finiteness, systems of nominal and verbal classification, and linguistic categorization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 4aAfrikanische Sprachen. 4aAtlantische Sprachen. 4aEegimaa. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican Languages.  aAtlantic Languages.  aBanjal.  aEegimaa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertMouton eBook Package 2022z97831107912970 cEPUBz97831106327670 cprintz978311059506240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311063632140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110636321423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110636321/original  a978-3-11-079129-7  Mouton eBook Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK